<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Artemisia</i> <i>cana</i> is dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Artemisia</i> <i>nova</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Chrysothamnus</i> spp., <i>Ericameria</i> <i>nauseosa</i>, <i>Rosa</i> <i>woodsii</i> or <i>Sarcobatus</i> <i>vermiculatus</i>. The herbaceous layer typically has cover of <i>Poa</i> <i>secunda</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is open to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse to continuous and usually grassy. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Artemisia cana</i> > 15% absolute cover in the shrub canopy (Manning and Padgett 1995).</li>
		
		<li><i>Artemisia cana</i> (ssp. <i>bolanderi</i>) is >60% relative cover in the shrub layer (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Playas, bottomlands, stream banks, swales, and snow catchments typically vernally wet. Soils are high in silt or clay and drain slowly. The USACE Wetland Inventory (2018 national list) recognizes <i>Artemisia cana</i> as a FACU plant. </div>
</div>

        
