<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Artemisia cana </i>is a relatively low, thickly branched, rounded shrub that rarely reaches 1 m in height. Leaves are silvery, canescent, and typically entire or rarely with 1-2 teeth. Plants often root sprout or layer. They reproduce by producing light, wind-dispersed seeds (Howard 2002a). <i>A. cana </i>ssp. <i>bolanderi </i>occurs in California and beyond in the Cascades and Great Basin; <i>A. cana </i>ssp. <i>cana </i>grows in the Rocky Mountains and Great Plains; <i>A. cana </i>ssp. <i>viscidula </i>is an intermountain shrub. <br/>
<br/>
Stands in California are usually structurally simple, consisting of <i>A. cana </i>ssp. <i>bolanderi </i>shrubs and understory grasses and sedges. The herbaceous layer may include vernal pool indicators such as <i>Psilocarphus brevissimus</i> and <i>Navarretia</i> spp. or more generally moist herbs such as <i>Hordeum brachyantherum, Muhlenbergia richarsonis</i>, and <i>Juncus</i> spp. (Boul et al. 2021b). <br/>
<br/>
Stands of this type occur on mesic sites including basin bottoms, stream terraces, swales, and flats (Boul et al. 2021b). These are often pluvial lakebeds in internally drained basins with alkaline, clay soils that are seasonally saturated from snowmelt accumulation (Young et al. 1977, 2007) and in snow catchments (Weixelman et al. 1999). This is one of the more rare sagebrush alliances in the state. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
