    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Artemisia cana</i> includes the Modoc Plateau (M261Ga-o), Mono (341Da-f, Dh-l), Northwestern Basin and Range (342Ba-e), and the Sierra Nevada (M261Ea, Ec, Ei-k, En-o, Er, Et).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Ga-o). Stands exist on riparian terraces and adjacent to vernal pools, ponds, and moist meadows, typically those with a long history of grazing (S. Smith 1998b). Young et al. (1977) described stands with <i>Elymus elymoides</i> in the understory from Willow Creek Valley in Lassen County.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Da-f, Dh-l). Stands occupy moist meadow and riparian edges, with descriptions from the Carson and Walker River watersheds (Weixelman et al. 1999), Sweetwater Range (Manning and Padgett 1995), Bridgeport Valley area (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b), and several subsections (S. Smith 1998b). They occur in areas with recurrent grazing and browsing of livestock with Achillea millefolium, Agropyron trachycaulum, Muhlenbergia richardsonis, and Poa pratensis.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Ba-e). Stands occur in moist, riparian lowlands throughout the section. Stands are extensive in the western Madeline Plain and are associated with stands of the <i>Juncus arcticus</i> (var. <i>balticus, mexicanus</i>) alliance.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea, Ec, Ei-k, En-o, Er, Et). Stands are common on the eastern slopes in riparian settings. Stands occupy moist meadow and riparian edges on the east side in Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) and along Long Valley Creek (S. Smith 1998b). They occur in areas with recurrent grazing and browsing of livestock with <i>Juncus arcticus, Achillea millefolium,</i> and other herbs (Manning and Padgett 1995).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Artemisia cana </i>is an important browse for domestic livestock and wildlife, especially in the winter (Howard 2002a). Prolonged livestock use can decrease the abundance of native bunchgrasses and increase the cover of shrubs and non-native species, such as <i>Poa pratensis</i> and <i>Taraxacum officinale</i>. Comparisons of grazed and protected (ungrazed) floodplain sites showed a tendency for Artemisia cana to occur more commonly in grazed than ungrazed sites with similar groundwater hydrology (NatureServe 2019). Many stands with <i>Achillea millefolium, Hymenoxys hoopesii, </i>and <i>Juncus arcticus </i>indicate past heavy grazing (Manning and Padgett 1995, S. Smith 1998b).

Unlike other <i>Artemisia</i> spp., <i>A. cana</i> resprouts vigorously following spring fire, and prescribed burning may increase shrub cover. Conversely, fire in the fall may decrease shrub abundance. (NatureServe 2019) </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
